18:57.000 --> 19:02.000
Community-oriented programs have gone away.

19:02.000 --> 19:05.000
What are the rates of young men in sports?

19:05.000 --> 19:07.000
Is it the way that it was when we were kids?

19:07.000 --> 19:10.000
Are less young men participating in sports?

19:10.000 --> 19:16.000
And where are the other healthy outlets for the young men in need of mentorship?

19:16.000 --> 19:18.000
So, sports is like most things.

19:18.000 --> 19:22.000
There's still the same level of participation, but unfortunately it's been crowded towards the wealthy.

19:22.000 --> 19:26.000
Engaging in a sport has become not a luxury item, but pretty close.

19:26.000 --> 19:30.000
Even if you look at the college athletes outside of basketball and football,

19:30.000 --> 19:34.000
it's disproportionately rich kids because if your kid wants to play lacrosse,

19:34.000 --> 19:37.000
to send them to lacrosse camps or hurdle lacrosse camps

19:37.000 --> 19:40.000
and get them the right training and the right equipment, it's just expensive.

19:40.000 --> 19:44.000
But I think sports and after-school programs are being cut,

19:44.000 --> 19:48.000
but going to solutions, I think there's a ton of solutions.

19:48.000 --> 19:54.000
So, starting boys a year late in elementary school, they're just less mature.

19:54.000 --> 19:58.000
The worst thing that happened to me or almost happened to me is my parents wanted me to skip a grade

19:58.000 --> 20:02.000
because it was back in the space race and if you were offered the opportunity to skip a grade,

20:02.000 --> 20:04.000
that meant you were going to be at work for NASA.

20:04.000 --> 20:11.000
I showed up at UCLA at the age of 17 and I was way too immature to handle the alcohol and the pressure of it all.

20:11.000 --> 20:16.000
Starting a year later, trying to create greater incentives to get more men in primary and secondary,

20:16.000 --> 20:20.000
high school and elementary school, more vocational programming.

20:20.000 --> 20:25.000
There's just a ton of jobs in the real economy for specialty construction, specialty nursing.

20:25.000 --> 20:30.000
Anyone who's renovating a house knows that a roofer makes really good money, much less a plumber,

20:30.000 --> 20:33.000
and stops shaming those jobs, start elevating them.

20:33.000 --> 20:37.000
I think we have to level up young people in general.

20:37.000 --> 20:40.000
There's been an enormous transfer of wealth from young people to old people.

20:40.000 --> 20:46.000
Specifically, people only the age of 40 used to control 19% of the GDP in terms of their wealth.

20:46.000 --> 20:47.000
It's been cut to 9%.

20:48.000 --> 20:52.000
The average 70-year-old is 72% wealthier than they were 40 years ago.

20:52.000 --> 20:56.000
The average person under the age of 40 is 24% less wealthy.

20:56.000 --> 21:00.000
And that affects women and men, but it's disproportionately affecting men

21:00.000 --> 21:07.000
because men are fairly or unfairly evaluated from a mating perspective based on their economic viability.

21:07.000 --> 21:12.000
The best example of, I think, that depicts this, the greatest innovation in history

21:12.000 --> 21:14.000
wasn't the iPhone or a semiconductor.

21:14.000 --> 21:16.000
It was the American middle class.

21:16.000 --> 21:21.000
Bought wars, pushed back on fascism, paid an enormous amount of taxes, was innovative,

21:21.000 --> 21:26.000
came up with DARPA, came up with vaccines, came up with GPS.

21:26.000 --> 21:30.000
And where it all started was 7 million men returned from World War II,

21:30.000 --> 21:32.000
and they demonstrated excellence in uniform.

21:32.000 --> 21:35.000
And the government said, we're going to make a massive investment in them

21:35.000 --> 21:38.000
in terms of the GI Bill and the highway construction bill.

21:38.000 --> 21:40.000
We're going to make jobs, we're going to make economic viability.

21:40.000 --> 21:42.000
And quite frankly, they were just very attractive.

21:42.000 --> 21:47.000
And they had an easier time finding mating, finding a house, two-car garage,

21:47.000 --> 21:49.000
and it set off the baby boom.

21:49.000 --> 21:54.000
And it set off a generation of confident, loving kids who were comfortable and said,

21:54.000 --> 21:55.000
all right, it's time for civil rights.

21:55.000 --> 21:57.000
It's time to bring women into the workforce.

21:57.000 --> 21:59.000
It's time for women's rights.

21:59.000 --> 22:05.000
And it just set off this kind of post-World War II liberal progressive society,

22:05.000 --> 22:08.000
the likes of which we've never seen that type of prosperity.

22:08.000 --> 22:10.000
But the middle class is an accident.

22:10.000 --> 22:11.000
It doesn't self-sustain.

22:11.000 --> 22:14.000
The incumbents and people on the far right will claim that the middle class

22:14.000 --> 22:16.000
is a self-repairing organism.

22:16.000 --> 22:17.000
It's not.

22:17.000 --> 22:18.000
It's an anomaly.

22:18.000 --> 22:20.000
Middle classes have never existed in society before.

22:20.000 --> 22:22.000
We figured it out.

22:22.000 --> 22:25.000
But unless you have economically and emotionally viable men,

22:25.000 --> 22:26.000
you can't have a middle class.

22:26.000 --> 22:29.000
So the question is, how do we level up young men?

22:29.000 --> 22:32.000
And I don't think you can just have affirmative action for men.

22:32.000 --> 22:34.000
I think that's too political.

22:34.000 --> 22:37.000
But I do think we have to put more money into the pockets of young people

22:37.000 --> 22:39.000
who have seen a transfer of wealth.

22:39.000 --> 22:41.000
And I'll touch a third rail here.

22:41.000 --> 22:43.000
Every year we transfer one and a half trillion dollars.

22:43.000 --> 22:47.000
The greatest economic transfer in history happens every year from young people

22:47.000 --> 22:50.000
to the wealthiest generation in history, senior citizens.

22:50.000 --> 22:52.000
And it's called social security.

22:52.000 --> 22:58.000
And it just is insane that this group that has consistently seen their wealth

22:58.000 --> 23:02.000
and on an inflation-adjusted basis, their livelihood go down and down and down,

23:02.000 --> 23:06.000
transfer money to the wealthiest population in the world.

23:06.000 --> 23:08.000
So let's talk more about economics.

23:08.000 --> 23:13.000
Mortgage tax deduction and capital gains are the two biggest deductions in our tax code.

23:13.000 --> 23:16.000
Who makes their money selling stocks and selling assets?

23:16.000 --> 23:17.000
Guys my age.

23:17.000 --> 23:19.000
Who makes their money with sweat?

23:19.000 --> 23:21.000
The guys in this room, the younger guys.

23:21.000 --> 23:22.000
Who owns homes?

23:22.000 --> 23:23.000
Older people.

23:23.000 --> 23:24.000
Who rents?

23:24.000 --> 23:25.000
Younger people.

23:25.000 --> 23:30.000
I feel like almost every economic policy is nothing but a thinly veiled transfer of wealth

23:30.000 --> 23:31.000
from the young to the old.

23:31.000 --> 23:36.000
And then the final one, the greatest intergenerational train robbery in history

23:36.000 --> 23:41.000
was the CARES Act in the transfer of wealth during COVID.

23:41.000 --> 23:44.000
Eighty-five percent of the money flushed into households was saved.

23:44.000 --> 23:46.000
It wasn't spent.

23:46.000 --> 23:50.000
So five of the seven trillion dollars wasn't spent on food or housing.

23:50.000 --> 23:55.000
It went into the markets, which absolutely sent the asset prices of real estate

23:55.000 --> 23:57.000
and stock markets screaming.

23:57.000 --> 23:59.000
Who owns homes and stocks?

23:59.000 --> 24:01.000
The incumbents and the old.

24:01.000 --> 24:07.000
The reason I'm rich is because in 2008, the government let the economy crash.

24:07.000 --> 24:09.000
It bailed out banks, but it didn't bail out the economy.

24:09.000 --> 24:10.000
I had a little bit of money.

24:10.000 --> 24:12.000
I was coming into my prime income earning years.

24:12.000 --> 24:18.000
So I was able to buy Apple and Amazon and Netflix at seven, four, and 10 bucks.

24:18.000 --> 24:19.000
Right?

24:19.000 --> 24:20.000
Yeah.

24:20.000 --> 24:22.000
Where the fuck did these guys put their money out?

