32:58.000 --> 32:59.000
and they'll say, what can we do?

32:59.000 --> 33:03.000
The first thing a corporation could do to make this better

33:03.000 --> 33:07.000
is to stop fetishizing graduates from elite universities.

33:07.000 --> 33:09.000
When I went to work for Morgan Stanley,

33:09.000 --> 33:12.000
they recruited at Stanford and Berkeley,

33:12.000 --> 33:14.000
and I was the first analyst I hired at UCLA.

33:14.000 --> 33:16.000
UCLA wasn't good enough for them.

33:16.000 --> 33:18.000
And I fell into the trap.

33:18.000 --> 33:20.000
When I started my company, I fetishized hiring people.

33:20.000 --> 33:23.000
We only hired people from Berkeley, Stanford, UCLA,

33:23.000 --> 33:24.000
and for some reason UVA.

33:24.000 --> 33:26.000
We had people from UVA.

33:26.000 --> 33:30.000
When you decide that you're only hiring from elite universities,

33:30.000 --> 33:33.000
you're saying, I'm not interested in single mothers.

33:33.000 --> 33:36.000
You're immediately excluding people who don't even have rich parents

33:36.000 --> 33:38.000
or are freakishly remarkable.

33:38.000 --> 33:41.000
So my recommendation, I was talking to the CEO of Salesforce

33:41.000 --> 33:42.000
about this,

33:42.000 --> 33:45.000
move away from a certification-based hiring strategy

33:45.000 --> 33:47.000
to a skills-based strategy.

33:47.000 --> 33:50.000
How do you figure out the testing, and it's expensive and it's hard

33:50.000 --> 33:55.000
to hire really talented young people that based on their skills

33:55.000 --> 33:57.000
as opposed to their certification?

33:57.000 --> 34:00.000
Because the reason we have entered into this LVMH strategy

34:00.000 --> 34:03.000
at elite universities is that corporations love it.

34:03.000 --> 34:05.000
People think our student is our consumer.

34:05.000 --> 34:07.000
No, our consumer is our product.

34:07.000 --> 34:09.000
Our consumer is the corporation.

34:09.000 --> 34:11.000
And the corporation is basically

34:11.000 --> 34:13.000
outsourced screening and hiring to these universities,

34:13.000 --> 34:16.000
thinking if they're only leading an 8% of their applicants,

34:16.000 --> 34:18.000
they must be pretty good.

34:18.000 --> 34:22.000
So corporations moving to a certification saying 10%, 20%,

34:22.000 --> 34:24.000
50% of our applicants.

34:24.000 --> 34:26.000
And I'm not talking about admin jobs.

34:26.000 --> 34:28.000
I'm talking about professional track jobs.

34:28.000 --> 34:31.000
Are going to be reserved for people based on a skills-based assessment

34:31.000 --> 34:33.000
where it is certification-blind.

34:33.000 --> 34:36.000
You couldn't get past the front desk without an elite university degree

